  <!-- 1. Quantities & Shorthands -->
  <section class="guide-section">
    <h2 id="quantities">1. Creating Quantities & Shorthands</h2>
    <p>
      A <code>Quantity</code> represents a physical quantity. It bundles a numerical value (magnitude), a <code>CompoundUnit</code>, and an optional standard deviation (uncertainty). You can instantiate quantities in three ways:
    </p>

    <h3>A. The Quantity Factory (<code>Q_</code>)</h3>
    <pre><code>from measurekit import Q_

# Standard value-unit construction
q1 = Q_(10, "m/s")

# Construction from string parsing (both value and unit)
q2 = Q_("9.81 m/s^2")

# Constructing with standard deviation
q3 = Q_(100, "degC", uncertainty=0.5)

# Constructing with a symbolic tracing name
q4 = Q_(2.5, "kg", symbol="mass")</code></pre>

    <h3>B. Syntactic Sugar (Unit Singletons)</h3>
    <p>
      MeasureKit generates static unit objects in <code>measurekit.units.core</code>. Right-side multiplication on these objects returns a <code>Quantity</code>:
    </p>
    <pre><code>from measurekit.units.core import m, s, kg

# Syntactic sugar for quantity creation
speed = 10 * m / s
force = 5.0 * kg * m / s**2

print(speed)              # (10.0) m/s
print(type(speed))        # &lt;class 'measurekit.domain.measurement.quantity.Quantity'&gt;</code></pre>

    <h3>C. Specialized Factories</h3>
    <p>
      If you are creating many quantities of the same unit, you can obtain a specialized factory using dictionary lookup:
    </p>
    <pre><code># Create a factory bound to "m/s^2"
accel_factory = Q_["m/s^2"]

a1 = accel_factory(9.81)
a2 = accel_factory(1.5, uncertainty=0.01)</code></pre>

    <h3>D. Attributes & Aliases</h3>
    <p>
      Quantities are optimized to bypass Python overhead wherever possible:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><code>.magnitude</code> (alias <code>.m</code>): Accesses the raw numerical value (scalar or tensor).</li>
      <li><code>.unit</code> (alias <code>.u</code>): Returns the <code>CompoundUnit</code> representation.</li>
      <li><code>.uncertainty</code>: Returns the standard deviation (1&sigma;), defaulting to <code>0.0</code>.</li>
      <li><code>.dimension</code>: Returns the physical dimension signature (e.g. <code>[length]</code>).</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <!-- 2. Unit Systems & Contexts -->
  <section class="guide-section">
    <h2 id="systems">2. Unit Systems & Contexts</h2>
    <p>
      MeasureKit resolves units against a <code>UnitSystem</code> built from configuration files (like <code>measurekit.conf</code>, <code>international.conf</code>, or <code>imperial.conf</code>). This contains definitions for dimensions, prefixes, units, and constants.
    </p>
    <p>
      You can create and swap unit systems thread-safely and async-safely using a context manager:
    </p>
    <pre><code>import measurekit as mk
from measurekit import Q_, system_context

# Default system is SI (international)
q_si = Q_(1, "ft")
print(q_si.to("m"))  # 0.3048 m

# Temporarily switch active system
with system_context("imperial.conf"):
    # Inside this context, imperial base units apply
    q_imp = Q_(1.0, "m")
    print(q_imp.to("ft"))  # 3.28084 ft</code></pre>
  </section>

  <!-- 3. Arithmetic & Temperature Offsets -->
  <section class="guide-section">
    <h2 id="arithmetic">3. Arithmetic & Temperature Offsets</h2>
    <p>
      MeasureKit enforces strict unit compatibility. Performing arithmetic operations between incompatible dimensions raises an <code>IncompatibleUnitsError</code>.
    </p>
    <pre><code>from measurekit import Q_, IncompatibleUnitsError

d = Q_(10, "m")
t = Q_(2, "s")

try:
    d + t
except IncompatibleUnitsError as e:
    print(f"Caught: &#123;e&#125;")  # Cannot operate with incompatible units: 'm' and 's'</code></pre>

    <h3>Absolute vs. Delta Temperature Offsets</h3>
    <p>
      Temperature units with offsets (like Celsius and Fahrenheit) require careful physical handling:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Absolute units</strong> (<code>degC</code>, <code>degF</code>, <code>K</code>) represent specific thermodynamic points.</li>
      <li><strong>Delta units</strong> (<code>delta_degC</code>, <code>delta_degF</code>) represent temperature differences.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      MeasureKit automatically handles absolute/delta conversions and arithmetic:
    </p>
    <pre><code># Subtracting two absolute temperatures yields a DELTA unit:
t1 = Q_(100, "degC")
t2 = Q_(90, "degC")
diff = t1 - t2
print(diff)                  # (10.0) delta_degC

# Adding a delta to an absolute temperature yields an absolute temperature:
t_final = t2 + Q_(15, "delta_degC")
print(t_final)               # (105.0) degC

# Trying to add two absolute temperatures is physically meaningless and raises an error:
try:
    t1 + t2
except IncompatibleUnitsError:
    print("Prevented physically meaningless operation!")</code></pre>
  </section>

  <!-- 4. Trigonometric & Transcendental Functions -->
  <section class="guide-section">
    <h2 id="transcendentals">4. Trigonometric & Transcendental Functions</h2>
    <p>
      MeasureKit defines trigonometric and transcendental methods on the <code>Quantity</code> class. They enforce physical consistency:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>The argument of the function must be dimensionless or an angle.</li>
      <li>Pure angles (like <code>degree</code>) are automatically converted to <code>radian</code> (the SI dimensionless angle) before calculation.</li>
      <li>Dimensionless ratio compounds (like <code>m/km</code>) are collapsed to their scale factor.</li>
      <li>Any other dimension raises a <code>DimensionError</code>.</li>
      <li>The return value is always a dimensionless quantity (unitless).</li>
    </ul>
    <pre><code>from measurekit import Q_, DimensionError
import math

# Angle automatically converted to radians
angle = Q_(90, "degree")
print(angle.sin())            # (1.0) 1  (dimensionless unity)

# Dimensionless ratio collapsed
ratio = Q_(10, "m") / Q_(1, "km") # 0.01 m/m
print(ratio.exp())            # (1.01005) 1

# Non-dimensionless raises DimensionError
try:
    Q_(5, "m").log()
except DimensionError as e:
    print(f"Dimension check failed: &#123;e&#125;")</code></pre>
    <p>
      Supported functions: <code>.sin()</code>, <code>.cos()</code>, <code>.tan()</code>, <code>.exp()</code>, <code>.log()</code>, <code>.tanh()</code>.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- 5. Uncertainty Propagation Details -->
  <section class="guide-section">
    <h2 id="uncertainty">5. Uncertainty Propagation Details</h2>
    <p>
      Uncertainties propagate automatically using first-order Taylor series expansion (rules of calculus). The propagation strategy adapts to the active <code>uncertainty_mode</code>:
    </p>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Mode</th><th>Method</th><th>Description</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><code>"python"</code> / <code>"gaussian"</code></td>
          <td>Analytical / Autograd</td>
          <td>Calculates derivatives exactly (default for standard Python/NumPy execution).</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>"monte_carlo"</code></td>
          <td>Stochastic Sampling</td>
          <td>Propagates uncertainty by drawing samples from distributions. (Defaults to 1000 samples, customizable).</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>"unscented"</code></td>
          <td>Unscented Transform</td>
          <td>Propagates uncertainty using sigma points (deterministic sampling).</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <pre><code>import measurekit as mk
from measurekit import Q_

# Run in Monte Carlo mode
with mk.uncertainty_mode("monte_carlo", samples=10000):
    x = Q_(10.0, "m", uncertainty=1.0)
    y = x ** 2
    print(f"Mean: &#123;y.magnitude:.3f&#125;, Std Dev: &#123;y.uncertainty:.3f&#125;")
    # Outputs stochastically: Mean ~101.0, Std Dev ~20.0</code></pre>
  </section>

  <!-- 6. Correlated Uncertainty & Covariance Store -->
  <section class="guide-section">
    <h2 id="covariance">6. Correlated Uncertainty & Covariance Store</h2>
    <p>
      By default, MeasureKit tracks variable correlations (meaning subtraction of a variable from itself is exactly zero). It uses two different mechanisms under the hood:
    </p>

    <h3>A. Lineage Tracking (Scalars)</h3>
    <p>
      For scalar values, <code>CovarianceModel</code> assigns a UUID to each independent quantity. When you perform math operations, it linearly combines the sensitivity coefficients:
      <code>c_new[uuid] = sum(jac_k * c_k[uuid])</code>.
    </p>
    <p>
      The final standard deviation is reconstructed as <code>sqrt(sum(c_new[uuid]^2))</code>.
    </p>

    <h3>B. Global Covariance Matrix (Arrays)</h3>
    <p>
      For array operations, a <code>CovarianceStore</code> tracks indices in a global covariance matrix. It propagates uncertainty blocks using affine transformations:
      <code>&Sigma;_out = J * &Sigma;_in * J.T</code>.
    </p>
    <p>
      You can isolate covariance tracking to a specific block using context managers:
    </p>
    <pre><code>import measurekit as mk
from measurekit import Q_, MeasureKitContext, PruningConfig

# Establish a scoped covariance context
with MeasureKitContext(backend_type="numpy") as store:
    # Variables allocated slices in the local store
    x = Q_([1.0, 2.0], "m", uncertainty=[0.1, 0.2])
    y = x * 2.0
    
# Clean isolation: store is pruned upon exiting the block</code></pre>
  </section>

  <!-- 7. Stateless Functional API for JAX -->
  <section class="guide-section">
    <h2 id="functional">7. Stateless Functional API for JAX</h2>
    <p>
      Global and context-local states (like <code>contextvars</code>) break when run inside JAX compile graphs (<code>jax.jit</code>, <code>jax.vmap</code>).
    </p>
    <p>
      MeasureKit solves this by providing a stateless functional API in <code>measurekit.functional</code>. In this mode, the covariance matrix and variable allocation metadata are stored explicitly inside a <code>FunctionalState</code> object that is threaded through function calls:
    </p>
    <pre><code>import jax
import jax.numpy as jnp
from measurekit import Q_
from measurekit.functional import FunctionalState, add, sub

# FunctionalState is a registered JAX pytree
state = FunctionalState()

x = Q_(jnp.array([1.0, 2.0]), "m", uncertainty=[0.1, 0.2])
y = Q_(jnp.array([3.0, 4.0]), "m", uncertainty=[0.3, 0.4])

# Operations return (result, new_state)
res, new_state = add(x, y, state)
diff, final_state = sub(res, x, new_state)

print(diff.uncertainty) # Standard deviation is correctly tracked!</code></pre>
  </section>

  <!-- 8. Multi-Backend & Lazy Loading -->
  <section class="guide-section">
    <h2 id="backends">8. Multi-Backend & Lazy Loading</h2>
    <p>
      MeasureKit polymorphically supports different array and tensor libraries. The <code>BackendManager</code> lazy-loads backends only on first call:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><code>numpy</code>: Standard NumPy array operations.</li>
      <li><code>torch</code>: PyTorch tensor operations.</li>
      <li><code>jax</code>: JAX array operations.</li>
      <li><code>python</code>: Standard Python floats and ints fallback.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      Importing <code>measurekit</code> is extremely fast because it does not import torch, JAX, or scipy until a tensor of that backend is passed to the factory.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- 9. JIT Compilation & Zero-Overhead Tracing -->
  <section class="guide-section">
    <h2 id="jit">9. JIT Compilation & Zero-Overhead Tracing</h2>
    <p>
      Standard Python execution of <code>Quantity</code> objects carries overhead due to class allocation and unit validation. For high-performance operations, MeasureKit supports two tracing mechanisms:
    </p>

    <h3>A. Native PyTorch/JAX compilation</h3>
    <p>
      When compiling via <code>torch.compile</code> or <code>jax.jit</code>, MeasureKit registers unit checks during the initial tracing phase. Once compiled, the unit checks are bypassed, and the final GPU kernel runs on raw tensors with **Zero-Overhead** (&lt;1.1&times; compared to raw PyTorch).
    </p>

    <h3>B. MeasureKit's own JIT compiler</h3>
    <p>
      For standard Python code, you can use the <code>@jit</code> decorator. It traces functions symbolically using <code>TracerQuantity</code> and a rust-backed <code>RationalUnit</code> representation, bakes a unit-less Python function using <code>exec</code>, and caches it:
    </p>
    <pre><code>from measurekit import Q_, jit

@jit
def kinetic_energy(mass, velocity):
    return 0.5 * mass * velocity ** 2

# Traced and compiled on first run
KE = kinetic_energy(Q_(70.0, "kg"), Q_(10.0, "m/s"))
print(KE)  # 3500.0 J (subsequent runs operate on raw baked kernel)</code></pre>
  </section>

  <!-- 10. Symbolic Math & Equation Solving -->
  <section class="guide-section">
    <h2 id="symbolic">10. Symbolic Math & Equation Solving</h2>
    <p>
      With the <code>[symbolic]</code> extra, MeasureKit integrates with SymPy to provide unit-aware symbolic math, derivatives, integration, and equation solving:
    </p>
    <pre><code>from measurekit.domain.symbolic.quantity import SymbolicQuantity, Equation

# Create atomic symbolic variables with units
x = SymbolicQuantity("x", "m")
t = SymbolicQuantity("t", "s")
v = SymbolicQuantity("v", "m/s")

# Equations enforce dimensional consistency at creation time
eq = Equation(x, v * t)

# Solve for a target variable symbolically
t_solved = eq.solve_for(t)
print(t_solved)            # Expression(x/v) [s]

# Differentiate or integrate expressions (updates units automatically)
v_expr = x.diff(t)
print(v_expr)             # Expression(x/t) [m/s]

# Evaluate the expression with concrete values
res = t_solved.evaluate(x=Q_(100, "m"), v=Q_(5, "m/s"))
print(res)                # 20.0 s</code></pre>
  </section>

  <!-- 11. Pandas Extensions & Accessors -->
  <section class="guide-section">
    <h2 id="pandas">11. Pandas Extensions & Accessors</h2>
    <p>
      MeasureKit registers a custom <code>.mk</code> accessor for Pandas Series containing Quantity objects, along with custom data types:
    </p>
    <pre><code>import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
from measurekit import Q_

# Create a Series with a strictly enforced unit type
series = pd.Series(
    [Q_(1.0, "m"), Q_(2.0, "m")],
    dtype="measurekit[m]"
)

# Access magnitudes, uncertainties, and units in bulk
print(series.mk.magnitude)      # pd.Series([1.0, 2.0])
print(series.mk.uncertainty)    # pd.Series([0.0, 0.0])
print(series.mk.unit)           # m

# Reconstitute the Series as a single vectorized Quantity array
array_q = series.mk.array
print(array_q)                  # [1.0 2.0] m (vectorized Quantity)

# Perform vectorized conversions
converted = series.mk.to("cm")
print(converted)                # Series of [100.0 cm, 200.0 cm]</code></pre>
  </section>

  <!-- 12. HDF5, xarray & State Serialization -->
  <section class="guide-section">
    <h2 id="io">12. HDF5, xarray & State Serialization</h2>
    <p>
      For saving data to disk, MeasureKit provides three serialization paths:
    </p>

    <h3>A. HDF5 Serialization (CF Conventions)</h3>
    <p>
      Saves the magnitude to a dataset and writes the unit to the dataset's attributes. Standard deviations are saved under an ancillary dataset:
    </p>
    <pre><code>import h5py
from measurekit.ext.io import to_hdf5, from_hdf5

q = Q_([1.0, 2.0], "m/s", uncertainty=[0.1, 0.2])

with h5py.File("data.h5", "w") as f:
    to_hdf5(q, f, "velocity")

# Reconstitute quantity with metadata
with h5py.File("data.h5", "r") as f:
    q_loaded = from_hdf5(f["velocity"])</code></pre>

    <h3>B. Xarray Accessor</h3>
    <pre><code>import xarray as xr

# Attaches units metadata to xarray datasets
da = xr.DataArray([10, 20], attrs=&#123;"units": "m/s"&#125;)
q = da.measurekit.quantify()
print(q)  # [10 20] m/s</code></pre>

    <h3>C. Application State Serialization</h3>
    <p>
      Pickling quantities directly can lose correlations tracked in the covariance matrix. Use <code>save_state</code> and <code>load_state</code> to serialize the active <code>CovarianceStore</code>:
    </p>
    <pre><code>from measurekit import save_state, load_state

# Saves the entire covariance matrix and registry
save_state("app_state.pkl")

# Restores the store to the active context
load_state("app_state.pkl")</code></pre>
  </section>

